		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Stormcrow at MN Territorials<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.43)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=4282'>Joshua "Stormcrow" Grace</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=4282&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 7, 2003</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> On Saturday, Outpost 2000 hosted the Minnesota Territorials. I hadn&#39;t played in any tournaments for a long time, but I wanted to play (despite the entry fee) to see how the game was changing, what sort of decktypes the top players were using, etc., etc. That, and I thought maybe I could win or do well.<br />
<br />
However, on Friday night, I went to my brother&#39;s apartment and playtested with him and his friend, Jordan. Caleb, my brother, beat the deck I&#39;d planned to play not once, but twice, and sent me into a furious cycle of deck building and deck destruction and deck rebuilding. At 3 AM, I was tired, decided to just slap together a deck that used as many of my favorite cards as possible--as many from the X-List as I could before I was no longer able to play them in top tournaments--and went to sleep.<br />
<br />
In the morning, I tested it against Caleb twice and Jordan once and swarmed them in all three games. I wasn&#39;t confident in my fellowship or in my chances to run to site 9, and I knew that Moria Swarm is somewhat weak against Gandalf and Secret Sentinels. Still, I didn&#39;t feel like expending any more energy on deckbuilding, it was noon, and the tournament started at 2 PM, a half-hour drive away.<br />
<br />
So, I stuck with my deck, posted on my homepage as Stormcrow&#39;s X-List Special: http://decktech.net/lotr/decks/decks.php?deck=28286<br />
<br />
17 players showed up, including 5 from St. Cloud (an hour drive), and several from Iowa (a longer drive).<br />
<br />
Check Scott Poster&#39;s report for players&#39; ratings if they interest you, but I suspected my two primary concerns would be Mitch Kimmes and Graham Neal.<br />
<br />
Game 1 vs Adam &quot;Louie&quot; Lewis<br />
<br />
He started Gimli, Sam, and Gollum in what I thought was the most interesting of all the fellowships I saw during the tournament. He bid 3 or so to go first, winning easily against my bid of 0.<br />
<br />
He moved to my site 2, faced a bunch of orcs and stopped. I played a number of cards, including Sting, Stung his hand, saw Ulaire Attea, and played just enough fellowship cards to deny Louie the twilight to play Attea.<br />
<br />
We moved on, site by site. He&#39;d go one and stop; I&#39;d go one and stop. He kept losing skirmishes to my orcs and taking wounds, but he repaired all his damage each fellowship with a slew of Hobbit Party Guests, The Gaffer, Rosie Cotton and Bilbo. On my end, I was doing fine, but I didn&#39;t want to pass him up--I wanted him to get to my site 7.<br />
<br />
Meanwhile, I could draw into a Swarms early enough for it to make a difference. He moved to 6, then finally launched an Attea at me when I moved to 5. I, however, shot it down with Aragorn&#39;s Bow.<br />
<br />
The next turn, he had to move to 7. I played enough orcs to overwhelm both Frodo and Sam. He couldn&#39;t use skirmish actions, so he lost.<br />
<br />
Game 2 vs Graham Neal<br />
<br />
Graham beat Scott Poster, another possible contender, in the first round. I expected Graham to play the Uruk Bomb, and he did, pairing it with a Rohan fellowship.<br />
<br />
He bid to go first and won skirmishes handily at the early sites, but the only important thing about those early skirmishes was that he didn&#39;t have the condition on the table to stack tokens for his victories and then discard my conditions later.<br />
<br />
I managed to keep up in the race, clogging his hand since he couldn&#39;t play any Uruks against me until site 4 or 5.<br />
<br />
He survived site 7, but lost Eomer in the process. I moved to 6 or 7, myself, having played enough characters to handle his Uruks easily. But, then, he had to move again, to site 8, and with only 4 companions--none of them defender +1--none of them with any direct damage/archery--he was defenseless against the 5 or 6 minions I played, and Frodo met an untimely demise.<br />
<br />
Game 3 vs Andy Kimmes<br />
<br />
At this point, only four players were left undefeated: Mitch Kimmes, my brother, Andy Kimmes and me. So, it was the Kimmeses against the Graces. Mitch and my brother finished their game first--Mitch won. It was up to me to maintain our family honor...<br />
<br />
Andy started Arwen and Greenleaf, played heavy archery and twilight denial, but my Scouts and Flankers were able to soak up enough wounds that I was still able to swarm an orc here and there.<br />
<br />
However, he had 4 Gondor Bowmen out early--all just waiting for a big turn of minions. I figured the swarm was probably not my best option, and I took the lead, moving into 6 after stalling him at 5 with the Cave Troll.<br />
<br />
He moved to 6 and played Pathfinder to put out his site 7, but he was wounded enough that he had to stop.<br />
<br />
On my turn I went to 7 and stopped, still holding the twilight down. Something like 7 total. He played a couple of Uruks, but they were nothing that Gorn with sword and bow, paired with Greenleaf, couldn&#39;t handle.<br />
<br />
He moved from 6 to 8, necessitating my double-jump, but I had a mini-explosion of characters, building my fellowship up to 7 or 8 and ran ahead, shooting everything down at 8, then continuing to 9 for the win.<br />
<br />
Graces 1 / Kimmes 1<br />
<br />
Game 4 vs Mitch Kimmes:<br />
<br />
Only Mitch and I were still undefeated at this point. Andy Kimmes blurts out something about how we&#39;re both playing Moria Swarm and ruins the surprise for both of us. By this time, I actually feel pretty confident about my deck, but I know that defeating another Moria Swarm deck will be a matter of having Aragorn&#39;s Bow, Greenleaf, Rumil and Sentinels all at the right time--as early as possible.<br />
<br />
Meanwhile, Caleb gets paired against Andy Kimmes. Graces versus the Kimmeses, round 2.<br />
<br />
Mitch bids 3 to my 0, decides that I bid 0 because I didn&#39;t care to go first, then makes me go first. Fine, I go first.<br />
<br />
He manages to play 1 card at site 2. I stop.<br />
<br />
He starts with Merry and an Ent and quickly builds his fellowship up to 5, playing Elrond and some other elf ally. I dump nearly my entire hand worth of shadow, and he stops.<br />
<br />
Gandalf is bad for me, so I figure I&#39;ll double where I can. Unfortunately, I have no early archery. I move to 3 and stop. He stops at 3. I move to 4 and stop. He stops at 4. This continues until I have to move to site 7, but before I do, I sting his hand, see what he has available, play all my companions and move. Mitch plays a cool Isengard orc combo which shuts down all my archery actions. Nonetheless, I still kill all his Armories with Sentinels, give him 2 archery and easily survive his mini-swarm with my 7 companions.<br />
<br />
Mitch moves to 8, and I deck myself, holding a Nertea and one or two orcs, realizing that there&#39;s no way I can stop him at 9.<br />
<br />
So I double, and somehow I make it. My fully-healed archers help a lot at 8, and a strength 7 or 9 Frodo and Cliffs of Emyn Muil help a lot at 9.<br />
<br />
Caleb loses again, failing to draw any of his Hides before site 7, giving Andy and his archery an easy run to 9.<br />
<br />
So, after 4 games, both potential Grace vs Kimmes match-ups are finalized and scored, and so far, it&#39;s a draw: Graces 2 / Kimmeses 2.<br />
<br />
As I&#39;m the only undefeated player at this point, others start talking to me about how I only need to win one more game to get into the finals for sure and such, and the pressure--what little there was--is largely off of me, especially as I&#39;ve played both Mitch and Graham.<br />
<br />
However, my next match against Nick Jenniges proves to be a squeaker.<br />
<br />
Game 5 vs Nick Jenniges:<br />
<br />
He starts Boromir and Merry and Frodo, OBH, drops Aragorn, RotN and takes the lead in the race. When I see three companions with the Gandalf signet, I suspect a Trust Me deck, and Gandalf shows up within a couple of sites.<br />
<br />
However, my choke is effective early on, and he wastes twilight, tossing minions against me that drain his twilight but stand no chance of wounding my characters. I double-move to 3, taking the lead.<br />
<br />
Unfortunately, he&#39;s playing Uruks, and my archery is slow to come together. I really feel I need Aragorn&#39;s Bow, his sword, Greenleaf *and* Orophin to plan to win the race, but they&#39;re slow to come together. Nenya helps immensely, as I do everything I can to cycle my deck, but I still don&#39;t have the whole set-up before I move to 4. I stop.<br />
<br />
Nick moves to 5 (a mistake on his part; it lets me put out my site 5), and I follow by doubling to 6. At 6, a Cave Troll puts the kibosh on his double-jump, and he stays.<br />
<br />
I move to 7 and stop, preparing a swarm, and take down Gandalf as he doubles to 8.<br />
<br />
Then, again, I dump 3 companions out of my hand and double from 7 to 9. Still choking him with Bill the Pony, 2x No Strangers on Aragorn and Faramir, and A Talent for Not Being Seen--spotting 4 Hobbits to reduce the twilight by 2. That&#39;s minus 5 twilight while I run with 7 companions. Even against Saruman and a mini-bomb at site 8, I my primary companions alive. With Saruman exhausted (and since Nick foolishly discarded an Uruk that only took one wound, not the two he needed to die), I double and finish his minions with Archery and Cliffs and Ranger&#39;s Sword.<br />
<br />
There&#39;s only one game left, and I learn that there&#39;s still a player I haven&#39;t played who&#39;s suffered only 1 loss. This concerns me a bit, since I haven&#39;t the foggiest idea who this player might be--but he spends a lot of time complaining about how an early mistake in reporting cost him a string of bad pairings that hurt his strength of schedule... Well, okay--he&#39;s 4 and 1, but he hasn&#39;t played anyone tough.<br />
<br />
He starts to play some little mindgames, shuffling my deck instead of cutting it, moving things around, talking a lot of nonsense. But I tune him out for the most part; after all, I&#39;ve already qualified for the final confrontation and don&#39;t care. At this point, I only want to beat him for the purity of the 6-0 and to get him to stop b****ing about his strength of schedule.<br />
<br />
Game 6 vs Nick Webber:<br />
<br />
He plays Rohan and Swarm, bidding high and forcing me to go first. I move a site per turn, always stopping, daring him to double, but he never does.<br />
<br />
Meanwhile, I draw an early Swarms and start stacking Flankers. I luck out and draw my Armories early, too (well, the luck was somewhat minimized by my proficient use of Nenya), and I start taking out his Rohan characters, eventually killing 2 of them with the Cave Troll at site 5. <br />
<br />
I move to his site 6, the Hornburg Armory, and stop. My Sentinels have taken out his conditions, and my archery&#39;s taken out his minions. I don&#39;t have more wounds than I can heal at the sanctuary if I have any wounds at all, so I feel good about moving to site 7.<br />
<br />
But before I have the chance, he moves into my fistful of Runners and Scouts who get Scimitars with Relics, and then I toss some Flankers from my Swarms, and it&#39;s goodnight, thanks for playing, and you have a better strength of schedule, now...<br />
<br />
So I managed to go 6-0 in the Open, and I was actually rather surprised by my deck&#39;s success. I trusted the Shadow a bit, but it was my Fellowship that really came through in the clutch games, getting me to 9 against all odds.<br />
<br />
However, I had plans with my other brother that were originally set for 6 PM, as when I&#39;d made them, I thought the tournament would start at Noon. Instead, since it started at 2, we finished the Open at quarter to 8. Mitch won his last game against his brother, Andy, so he was the only 5-1 player and was scheduled to face me in the final confrontation. I knew I had a good chance of besting him 2/3, but I also knew that it was a matter of the luck of the draw. And, in the meantime, I really wanted to go since I was nearly 2 and a half hours late (factoring in driving time).<br />
<br />
Thus, I originally offered to give him 1st and split the 1st and 2nd prize support. He would have accepted, but he looked as though he&#39;d feel a tookeated by getting 1st that way. So, I decided to start a game really quickly, giving him the confrontation if he won the game, playing through if I won (I guess, though it wasn&#39;t an issue).<br />
<br />
Our game progressed much as the first, except I couldn&#39;t get my Sentinels to my hand early, allowing him to do a lot more damage with his Orcs than he did in our earlier match-up. Nonetheless, I moved to site 7 with Aragorn (sword and bow), Greenleaf, Merry, Pippin and Frodo with Sting, O Elbereth, Mithril-coat and There and Back Again. He played the Caves, of course, as I would have. So, no skirmish events. Meanwhile, he dumps a load of minions, including the Isengard orc combo to block my archery actions. I kill his remaining Armories and give him two archery, but none of his minions die. I assign incorrectly, forgetting site 7&#39;s text as I&#39;m glancing at my watch, and Mitch doesn&#39;t forget. He reminds me as I try to kill one of the 3 orcs skirmishing Frodo with a Cliffs that I get no skirmish actions. Okay, then, I shake his hand, say Good game, collect some packs (my first from Helms Deep) and drive 90 MPH to Minneapolis.<br />
<br />
It was fun.<br />
<br />
I hope you get a chance to play Mitch at Day 2 of Worlds.<br />
<br />
And I hope he beats you all... *evil cackle*<br />
<br />
In the meantime, I suppose I&#39;ll have to figure out the Standard Tournament scene.<br />
<br />
Enjoy,<br />
Joshua &quot;Stormcrow&quot; Grace <br></font></blockquote><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/treports/treports.php?id=4326&view=1&PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/treports/treports.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
